e my longstanding skepticism of the games business outside of cloud gaming =
was looking pretty justified. And then came that banner.

Let me be blunt: while there are cases to be made against this acquisition,=
 I think the specific argument used by the CMA is a very poor one, and not =
just because the agency couldn=E2=80=99t be bothered to not seem biased tow=
ards Sony in its Twitter graphic at the head of an emoji-filled thread that=
 was honestly pretty embarrassing for a government agency making multi-bill=
ion dollar decisions:

The CMA's tweet featured a PlayStation controller ( https://twitter.com/ben=
thompson/status/1651188497926193153 )

Actually, now that I think about it, it=E2=80=99s good that the CMA=E2=80=
=99s graphic included a PlayStation controller, given that the press releas=
e ( https://www.gov.uk/government/news/microsoft-activision-deal-prevented-=
to-protect-innovation-and-choice-in-cloud-gaming ) didn=E2=80=99t include a=
 single mention of Sony or PlayStation; the only mention of =E2=80=9Cconsol=
es=E2=80=9D was this paragraph:

The deal would reinforce Microsoft=E2=80=99s advantage in the market by giv=
ing it control over important gaming content such as Call of Duty, Overwatc=
h, and World of Warcraft. The evidence available to the CMA indicates that,=
 absent the merger, Activision would start providing games via cloud platfo=
rms in the foreseeable future. The cloud allows UK gamers to avoid buying e=
xpensive gaming consoles and PCs and gives them much more flexibility and c=
hoice as to how they play. Allowing Microsoft to take such a strong positio=
n in the cloud gaming market just as it begins to grow rapidly would risk u=
ndermining the innovation that is crucial to the development of these oppor=
tunities.

The key issue here, as is so often the case in antitrust decisions, revolve=
s around market definition. In this case the CMA considered cloud gaming as=
 a completely separate market from console gaming; given that Microsoft is =
the largest player in cloud gaming, it ought not be allowed to acquire Acti=
vision. There is zero consideration given to the point in this paragraph, w=
hich is that cloud gaming is an alternative to console gaming precisely bec=
ause it is competitive with cloud gaming, which means it is a part of the s=
ame market.

What makes this narrow definition even dumber is the way in which the CMA e=
nded up at this decision:

* In February ( https://www.gov.uk/government/news/microsoft-activision-dea=
l-could-harm-uk-gamers ) the CMA provisionally found that Microsoft was lik=
ely to harm both the cloud gaming market and the console market (and yes, t=
hese two were found to be distinct); the latter determination was bizarre b=
ecause Sony continues to dominate the console market =E2=80=94 PlayStation =
had 45% of the market in 2022, followed by Nintendo at 28% and Microsoft at=
 27% =E2=80=94 which means the CMA=E2=80=99s declaration that Microsoft was=
 likely to stop selling =E2=80=9CCall of Duty=E2=80=9D on PlayStation made =
no sense.
* In March ( https://www.gov.uk/government/news/cma-narrows-scope-of-concer=
ns-in-microsoft-activision-review ) the CMA basically said =E2=80=9CWhoops!=
=E2=80=9D and admitted that it made zero economic sense for Microsoft to no=
t sell =E2=80=9CCall of Duty=E2=80=9D on PlayStation; the response, though,=
 was to remove the console market from consideration, leaving just the clou=
d gaming market (as an aside, this response almost certainly came from Micr=
osoft making its case, which raises the question as to whether the company =
failed to make its case previously).

Again, as I noted above, if =E2=80=9Ccloud gaming=E2=80=9D is your market d=
efinition, then of course this acquisition should be blocked: there is no q=
uestion that =E2=80=9CCall of Duty=E2=80=9D and Activision=E2=80=99s other =
titles are only going to be available for a subscription as part of Microso=
ft=E2=80=99s offering. This market definition, though, is stupid: =E2=80=9C=
Call of Duty=E2=80=9D will, as the CMA admitted in March, still be for sale=
 on an a la carte basis as it always has been for PlayStation (or Xbox for =
that matter, and if the acquisition is approved, the Nintendo Switch and Nv=
idia GeForce NOW streaming service). To say that those four alternatives ar=
e not competitive with Xbox GamePass, simply because the business model is =
different, is not to affirm competition, but to deny it.

The incredible thing about the CMA decision, though, is that not only does =
it deny meaningfully new competition to Sony=E2=80=99s PlayStation dominanc=
e, it very well may cement it. I wrote in an Update earlier this year ( htt=
ps://stratechery.com/2023/meta-and-the-quest-pro-meta-and-vr-as-console-mic=
