Notice that this is for games that are purchased, and keep in mind that Mic=
rosoft=E2=80=99s goal with the Activision acquisition is not to gain exclus=
ive games to sell but rather games to subscribe to. As I=E2=80=99ve argued =
the only way this acquisition makes sense is the extent to which it makes p=
ossible a new business model for gaming; simply buying exclusives via estab=
lished titles like Call of Duty would be hugely value destructive.

What is notable about Microsoft=E2=80=99s subscription push is that it alig=
ns the company=E2=80=99s Xbox division with Microsoft=E2=80=99s overall pus=
h towards cloud computing and subscription services. What is interesting to=
 consider are two questions:

* First, would Microsoft have ever gone down this path absent the investmen=
t in its original (failed) Xbox strategy? I would argue the answer is no; t=
his is a reasonable leveraging of Xbox assets, but I do wonder if Microsoft=
 could go back two decades if they would even bother.
* Second, if regulators were to kill this deal (Microsoft still needs appro=
val from the UK and the US) would Xbox be long for this world? It=E2=80=99s=
 hard to see how the division makes sense if Microsoft has the current busi=
ness model dictated to them, given just how dominant Sony is with said busi=
ness model.

Microsoft is going to appeal this decision; if they fail, and pull out of c=
onsole gaming entirely, the CMA will have not just unwittingly reproduced a=
 PlayStation controller, but ensured Sony is dominant in consoles for a ver=
y long time to come.

Microsoft and Google Earnings
-----------------------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-04-26/microso=
ft-sees-ai-shaking-up-search-while-google-calms-investors ) :

Alphabet Inc.=E2=80=99s Google and Microsoft Corp., whose quarterly earning=
s each got a boost from their established search and cloud-computing busine=
sses, used their time with investors to emphasize what=E2=80=99s next: arti=
ficial intelligence.

In their respective earnings calls on Tuesday, the tech giants, which are b=
ecoming rivals in the competition for the future of search, offered up star=
kly different assessments of just how much disruption is in store for the m=
arket. Google executives encouraged investors to trust in the company=E2=80=
=99s long track record as the world=E2=80=99s leading search engine, and fr=
amed AI as just another shift in its constantly evolving business. Microsof=
t suggested that something much more dramatic is underway.

Investors seemed to like Microsoft=E2=80=99s thesis better, sending its sha=
res up as much as 7.7% in premarket trading before New York exchanges opene=
d, while Alphabet increased less than 2%.

I originally was going to break down Microsoft and Google=E2=80=99s earning=
s separately, but this Bloomberg article nicely frames one of the points I =
was going to make =E2=80=94 and thanks to the CMA, I=E2=80=99m running out =
of room so I=E2=80=99ll stick with this.

First Google; Chief Business Officer Philipp Schindler said in his prepared=
 remarks ( https://seekingalpha.com/article/4596558-alphabet-inc-goog-q1-20=
23-earnings-call-transcript ) :

First, Google AI. I=E2=80=99ve said before, AI has long been an important d=
river of our business. Advancements are powering our ability to help busine=
sses, big and small, respond in real time to rapidly changing market and co=
nsumer shifts and deliver measurable ROI when it=E2=80=99s needed most. In =
Q1, we continue to innovate across our products. Take Core Search, for exam=
ple. In targeting, we updated search keyword relevance using the latest nat=
ural language AI from MUM models to improve the relevance and performance o=
f shown ads when there are multiple overlapping keywords eligible for an au=
ction. In bidding, we improved our Smart Bidding models to bid more accurat=
ely based on differences in search ad formats. In other words, bid more eff=
ectively depending on how a user wants to engage with an ad. In creatives, =
we opened our automatically created assets beta to all advertisers in Engli=
sh. ACA generates text assets alongside your responsive search ads and uses=
 AI to help reduce the amount of manual work to keep creatives fresh and re=
levant to users=E2=80=99 query, context and to the advertisers business.

I don=E2=80=99t know who first made this observation, but it is absolutely =
the case that as soon as AI is productized by big tech companies it immedia=
tely becomes machine learning; once it is available as a service it is anal=
ytics; once it is leverageable by individuals it is simply an Excel functio=
n. In this Google has a point: the company has been talking about AI for a =
long time in terms of its products; to the extent Google deploys generative=
 AI for advertising ( https://www.ft.com/content/36d09d32-8735-466a-97a6-86=
8dfa34bdd5 ) is the degree to which Google will immediately have the most f=
inancially meaningful deployment of AI in tech.

Moreover, Google Cloud is now officially profitable, although that is cavea=
ted by the inclusion of Google Workspace in reporting, a change in timing a=
s far as stock-based compensation is concerned, and a change in how Google =
depreciates hardware; what is important, though, is that Google Cloud is th=
e best way to access Google=E2=80=99s AI capabilities, potentially providin=
g meaningful differentiation. Sure, Google is going to be very hesitant to =
disrupt search, but its AI capabilities are not going completely to waste.

Microsoft, on the other hand, could not have been more eager to frame AI as=
 something new, and for good reason. Note this answer from Satya Nadella on=
 the Microsoft earnings call ( https://seekingalpha.com/article/4596556-mic=
rosoft-corporation-msft-q3-2023-earnings-call-transcript ) in response to a=
 question about Azure demand:

The third is perhaps more of a relative statement because of some of the wo=
rk we=E2=80=99ve done in AI even in the last couple of quarters, we are now=
 seeing conversations we never had, whether it=E2=80=99s coming through you=
 and just OpenAI=E2=80=99s API, right? If you think about the consumer tech=
 companies that are all spinning essentially Azure meters, because they hav=
e gone to open AI and are using their API. These were not customers of Azur=
e at all. Second, even Azure OpenAI API customers are all new, and the work=
load conversations, whether it=E2=80=99s B2C conversations in financial ser=
vices or drug discovery on another side, these are all new workloads that w=
e really were not in the game in the past, whereas we now are.

